SECTION 1 — Species Diversity: Definition and Scope
The variety of life — the most fundamental concept in ecology
1.1 What is Species Diversity?
Species diversity is the variety of species in a given area or community. It is the most commonly used
measure of biodiversity and includes both the number of species (species richness) and the evenness
of their distribution (species evenness).
Biodiversity (biological diversity) was popularised by E.O. Wilson (1988) and refers to the variety of
life on Earth at all its levels — genetic, species, and ecosystem diversity.
