4.2 Species-Area Relationship
Proposed by Preston (1962) and developed by MacArthur & Wilson (1967) — Theory of Island
Biogeography. As the area of a habitat increases, the number of species also increases but at a
decreasing rate.
Formula: S = cA^z log S = log c + z log A Where: S = number of species | A = area | c = constant
(depends on taxon) | z = slope (0.1–0.2 for mainland; 0.2–0.35 for islands) Implication: Doubling the
area does NOT double the species. A 10× increase in area typically doubles species richness. This is
why habitat fragmentation is so devastating to biodiversity.
