SECTION 6 — Edge Effect
Why ecotones have higher species diversity
6.1 Definition of Edge Effect
The edge effect is the tendency for greater variety and density of organisms to occur at the boundary
(ecotone) between two ecosystems compared to either ecosystem alone. The ecotone supports species
from both communities PLUS edge species that are unique to the boundary zone.
Edge Effect — Species Richness Across an Ecotone
