8.2 Historical Development of Niche Concept
Joseph Grinnell (1917) First used "niche" in ecology to mean the habitat requirements of a species —
the spatial niche. He studied California Thrasher and defined its niche as the
microhabitat it occupies. "Where does the species live?" — spatial aspect.
Charles Elton (1927) Defined niche as the functional role of an organism in the community — its
food, its enemies, its relationships. Focused on TROPHIC niche — "What
does the species do?" — the animal's job in the community.
G. Evelyn Hutchinson
(1957)
Most comprehensive definition: niche as an n-dimensional hypervolume —
a multi-dimensional space defined by all environmental variables
(temperature, humidity, food size, pH, etc.) within which a species can
survive and reproduce. Each variable is one dimension of the niche.
Introduced Fundamental vs Realised niche distinction.
Eugene Odum (1971) Simplified as: "Habitat is the organism's address; niche is its
profession." This analogy is the most famous description of niche and is
DIRECTLY asked in NET.
