SECTION 10 — Competitive Exclusion & Resource Partitioning
Gause's Law and how species avoid it
10.1 Competitive Exclusion Principle (Gause's Law)
Proposed by G.F. Gause (1934) based on laboratory experiments with Paramecium. States: "Two
species competing for the same limiting resource cannot coexist indefinitely — one will
outcompete and eliminate the other."
Also stated as: "Complete competitors cannot coexist" or "No two species can occupy the same
niche at the same time and place indefinitely."
Gause's Experiments:
• Grew Paramecium aurelia and P. caudatum separately ® both survived
• Grew them TOGETHER competing for same food (bacteria) ® P. aurelia won, P. caudatum
eliminated
• Grew P. caudatum and P. bursaria together ® COEXISTED because they used different food
resources (P. bursaria ate yeast; P. caudatum ate bacteria)
• Conclusion: coexistence requires niche differentiation
10.2 Resource Partitioning
Resource partitioning is the mechanism by which competing species avoid the competitive exclusion
principle by dividing resources among themselves — each specialising on a slightly different part of the
resource spectrum. This allows coexistence by reducing niche overlap.
Example How Partitioning Works
MacArthur's Warblers (1958) Five warbler species in same spruce tree fed at different vertical zones — tip, upper
canopy, middle, lower branches, trunk. Classic example of spatial niche partitioning.
Darwin's Finches Different beak sizes allow exploitation of different seed/food types on Galapagos
Islands. Trophic niche partitioning after adaptive radiation.
Lizard communities in
deserts
Different lizard species active at different times of day (morning, midday, evening) —
temporal niche partitioning.
Coral reef fish Different species feed at different depths, times, and on different food types — multiple
dimensions of niche partitioning in same space.
Indian hornbills Different hornbill species take different sized fruits from same fruiting trees — trophic
niche partitioning by body/bill size.
10.3 Character Displacement
Character displacement occurs when two competing species evolve to become MORE DIFFERENT
from each other where their ranges overlap, reducing competition. Classic example: Darwin's Ground
Finches — beak sizes diverge more in sympatry than in allopatry. Another example: Darwin's Rock
Nuthatches (Brown & Wilson, 1956 — who coined the term).
