n KEY FACTS FOR UGC NET — Unit 3.5
4 1. a, b, g diversity coined by R.H. Whittaker (1960)
4 2. b = g/a | g = a × b — formulas must be memorised
4 3. Shannon-Wiener Index H' = -S(pi × ln pi) — measures richness + evenness
4 4. Simpson Index D = Spi² — measures dominance; HIGHER D = LOWER diversity
4 5. Jaccard Index = presence/absence similarity | Sorensen = weighted similarity
4 6. Species-Area relationship: S = cA^z | MacArthur & Wilson (1967)
4 7. z = 0.1-0.2 for mainland habitats | z = 0.2-0.35 for oceanic islands
4 8. Ecotone coined by Clements (1905) — transition zone between two ecosystems
4 9. Edge effect = higher species diversity at ecotone than in either habitat
4 10. Intermediate Disturbance Hypothesis — Connell (1978) — max diversity at intermediate
disturbance
4 11. Grinnell (1917) = first niche concept (spatial) | Elton (1927) = trophic niche
4 12. Hutchinson (1957) = n-dimensional hypervolume niche concept
4 13. "Habitat = address; Niche = profession" — Eugene Odum (1971)
4 14. Fundamental niche > Realised niche always (biotic interactions reduce niche)
4 15. Competitive Exclusion Principle = Gause's Law (1934) — no two species same niche
